Customer Segmentation - Connie Xavier¶

Problem Definition and Information¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year to improve market penetration. The Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

As a Data scientist at AllLife Bank, I need to identify different segments in the existing customer base, based on their spending patterns as well as past interactions with the bank and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Objective¶

To explore and visualize the data, use clustering algorithms to segment the existing customers, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the bank.

Key Questions¶

  1. Is there a good clustering algorithm to segment the existing customers?
  2. How many different groups/clusters of countries can be found from the data?
  3. What are the key factors distinguishing the different clusters of customers?
  4. What improvements can the bank make to market and service these customers?

Data Information¶

Each record in the database represents a customer's information. A detailed data dictionary can be found below.

Data Dictionary

  • Sl_No: Primary key of the records
  • Customer Key: Customer identification number
  • Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
  • Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
  • Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  • Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  • Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Feature Scaling¶

Feature scaling is specially relevant in machine learning models that compute some sort of distance metric, like most clustering methods. So, scaling should be done to avoid the problem of one feature dominating over others because the unsupervised learning algorithm uses distance to find the similarity between data points.

We will scale the variables in the datasets since they all have different ranges.

Part 3: K Means Clustering¶

In [277]:
# We will look at the results for 1-8 clusters
clusters = range(1, 9)  # define # of clusters
meanDistortions = []  # Create a empty list

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)  # Initialize KMeans
    model.fit(scaled_df)  # Fit kMeans on the data
    prediction = model.predict(scaled_df)  # Predict the model on the data
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / scaled_df.shape[0]  # Find distortion
    )

    meanDistortions.append(
        distortion
    )  # Append distortion values to the empty list created above

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")  # Title of X-axis
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")  # Title of y-axis
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)  # Title of the plot

Silhouette Score¶

Silhouette score is one of the methods for evaluating the quality of clusters created using clustering algorithms such as K-Means. It is a measurement of how similar points within a cluster are to each other compared to how similar those points are to neighboring clusters. Silhouette coefficients near +1 indicate that the sample is far away from the neighboring clusters.

In [278]:
sil_score = []  # Create empty list
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))  # Creating a list of range from 2 to 10
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)  # Initializing KMeans algorithm
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((scaled_df))  # Predicting on the data
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(scaled_df, preds)  # Cacalculating silhouette score
    sil_score.append(score)  # Appending silhouette score to empty list created above
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Average Silhouette Score")

  • From the silhouette scores, it seems that 3 is a good value of k since it has the highest silhouette score (0.52).
  • Let's do deeper investigation for different K values using SilhouetteVisualizer.

SilhouetteVisualizer¶

Below are the points that every cluster needs to satisfy for selecting the optimal K-value.

  • There should be no negative silhouette coefficent value
  • All the clusters should cross the avg silhouette score
  • All the clusters should have the different variations (width)
  • All the clusters should have different silhouette score

Note:

  1. Width of each cluster refers to the size of each cluster. (Number of data points present in each cluster)
  2. Horizontal line refers to the Silhouette score of each cluster.
  3. Dotted red line is an Average Silhouette score.
In [279]:

visualizer.fit(scaled_df)
visualizer.show()

We can see from the plot above that K=3 clusters meet the requirements. So, let's take 3 as the appropriate no. of clusters (K) as the average silhouette score is the highest, the silhouette plot meets all the criteria, and there is a knick at 3 in the elbow curve.

Part 4: Hierarchical Clustering¶

Cophentic Correlation¶

The cophenetic correlation coefficient is a correlation coefficient between the cophenetic distances (Dendrogramic distance) obtained from the tree, and the original distances used to construct the tree. It is a measure of how faithfully a dendrogram preserves the pairwise distances between the original unmodeled data points.

The cophenetic distance between two observations is represented in a dendrogram by the height of the link at which those two observations are first joined. That height is the distance between the two subclusters that are merged by that link.

Cophenetic correlation is the way to compare two or more dendrograms.

In [293]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]
cophenet_corr = []
linkage_methods_names = []
distance_metrics_names = []
# loop through distance metrics and linkage methods
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        cophenet_corr.append(c)
        linkage_methods_names.append(lm)
        distance_metrics_names.append(dm)
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Part 6: Compare Clusters¶

  • K Means algorithm took much less time for execution compared to Hierarchical Clustering, which makes sense since Hierachical Clustering computes the distance between every pair of rows. The most time consuming portion was creating the dendrograms for Hierarchical Clustering.
  • K Means obtained a higher number of recommended clusters (3) than Hierarchical Clustering (2).
  • The average silhouette score for Hierarchical Clustering (0.57) was higher than K Means (0.52).
  • Cluster 2 in K Means had the same observations as Cluster 1 in Hierarchical Clustering (50 observations).
  • Both algorithms produced distinct clusters. Using two or three clusters showed the differences in average credit limit, number of credit cards, and number of online visits. There was a cluster at the lower range of these variables, and the other clusters were at the moderate or high end.
  • However, three clusters was a better breakup of the data since it identified the difference in number of bank visits and number of calls. For example, Hierarchical Clustering with two clusters showed one cluster spanning all possible values for these variables. With K means and three clusters, we were able to see that Cluster 0 made a high number of calls and Cluster 1 made a high number of visits to the bank compared to other clusters.
  • When comparing Hierarchical Clustering with 3 clusters and K Means with 3 clusters with PCA, the results were very similar. The only difference was in a few points that were on the borderline between two of the clusters.

Part 7: Conclusions and Recommendations¶

Summary/Insights¶

Data Background:

  • There are 660 rows and 7 columns in the data.
  • Duplicated values in Customer Key were kept in the data.
  • All columns were int type.
  • There were no missing values.

Data Preprocessing:

  • The Sl_No and Customer Key columns were dropped as it isnt important to the analysis.
  • Outliers were identified in several of the highly skewed variables. However, these were kept as they were in a reasonable range.
  • Standardized all numerical features with StandardScaler.

Observations from EDA:

  • Most customers hold four credit cards (22.9%), make two bank visits (23.9%), two online visits (28.6%) and four calls (16.4%) yearly.
  • Very few customers (~7.9%) make six or more online visits in a year.
  • There is a significant drop in percentage of customers making five or more calls a year or holding eight or more credit cards. Most customers have fewer contacts or interactions with the bank.
  • Total_Credit_Cards and Avg_Credit_Limit have a moderately high positive correlation (0.61).
  • Total_calls_made and Total_Credit_Cards have a moderately high negative correlation (-0.65).
  • No two variables are very highly correlated to each other.
  • Generally, as a customer chooses more of one type of interaction, the less likely the customer will make more of any other type of interaction with the bank.

Clustering Analysis:

K Means

  • Took 3 as the appropriate no. of clusters (K) as the average silhouette score is the highest, the silhouette plot meets all the criteria, and there is a knick at 3 in the elbow curve.
  • Overall, all the clusters cover different ranges of average credit limit and number of credit cards. Cluster 2 prefers online interactions, Cluster 1 prefers bank visits, and Cluster 0 prefers calls.

Hierarchical Clustering

  • Compared the cophenetic correlations of different distance metrics/linkage methods. Euclidean distance with average linkage had the highest value.
  • Compared dendrograms of the top 5 cophenetic correlations as well as linkage methods for euclidean distance metric. Euclidean with ward had the most distinct clusters in the dendrogram.
  • Compared the silhouette scores for Euclidean distance with average linkage vs ward linkage and ultimately chose Euclidean/average with 2 clusters.
  • The clusters produced two distinct clusters except for total bank visits and total calls made.

Comparing Clusters

  • K Means took less time and produced more clusters.
  • The average silhouette score for Hierarchical Clustering (0.57) was higher than K Means (0.52).
  • Cluster 2 in K Means had the same observations as Cluster 1 in Hierarchical Clustering (50 observations).
  • Using three clusters vs. two clusters was a better breakup of the data.

Recommendations¶

Recommendations below are based on K Means

  • Cluster 0 consists of customers who have a lower credit limit, lower number of credit cards, and prefer making calls to the bank. The bank has the biggest opportunity to upsell services to these customers as they hold a low number of credit cards. The bank should focus on hiring and training customer service representatives to provide better quality call service and be ready to market to these customers when they call. Follow-ups and check ins can be done through text or phone call.

  • Cluster 1 customers have a moderate credit limit, moderate number of credit cards, and prefer making visits to the bank. This was the largest group of customers. This is also an opportunity to upsell services. These customers prefer in-person interactions, so it is important to be personable. The bank can look at making these customers more comfortable when they visit the bank like offering a beverage and making light conversation. Schedule follow-ups visits as needed and provide information through mail as well.

  • Cluster 2 customers have a high credit limit and high number of credit cards and prefer online visits. Since these are already high credit users, the bank should focus on promoting other banking offers like loans to these customers. Since these customers seem to prefer digital transcations, follow up with users through e-mail.

  • Since high credit users prefer and continue using online services, it may be good to encourage online banking services to the other groups of customers as well.

  • To better analyze how to improve service to customers, it is recommended that the bank conduct surveys or obtain ratings from customers after each interaction. Tracking this metric will help show if there is an improvement.
